00:01:57.199 --> 00:02:02.360
dplyr provides four functions, each dedicated to doing one of these things, and let's take

00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:07.919
a look at them, starting with select. So, select is very simple. It's a way for you

00:02:07.919 --> 00:02:13.199
to just pull out variables or columns from a data frame. So if I only wanted the storm

00:02:13.199 --> 00:02:18.080
column and the pressure column from the storm's data frame, then I could select from storms

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:22.199
the storm and pressure column. And you could list as many column names or as few column

00:02:22.199 --> 00:02:26.419
names as you want there, and it'll bring back everything you list. So that's easy enough

00:02:26.419 --> 00:02:32.000
to do in R, and you might ask, why would you use select to do it? Well, one thing that

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:37.039
select does is it provides more ways to specify which columns you want. So you'll know that

00:02:37.039 --> 00:02:41.360
if you use brackets and integer subsetting, you put a negative sign in front of an integer

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:46.639
and that stands in R, for giving you everything except this integer. With select, you can

00:02:46.639 --> 00:02:50.720
put a negative sign in front of a name, and you'll get back everything except that name.

00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:57.339
So here we did everything except the storm column. You could also use the colon notation

00:02:57.339 --> 00:03:01.119
to get a range of variables. So this would say, giving back the win variable, the date

00:03:01.119 --> 00:03:06.559
variable, and any variable that appears in between them. So that'd do the same as the

00:03:06.559 --> 00:03:11.679
previous command. And then there's other functions that you can use inside of select,

00:03:11.679 --> 00:03:19.679
come with dplyr, that make it even easier. So here's a list of those functions. And you

00:03:19.679 --> 00:03:24.399
can see they allow you to pull out columns whose names have a certain string in them

00:03:24.399 --> 00:03:29.759
or a certain regular expression or begin with a certain word or end with a certain word

00:03:29.759 --> 00:03:34.600
or is in a group of names and so on. So if you have a very large data set, selecting

00:03:34.600 --> 00:03:38.199
variables out of it might be an important task, and these functions might make it very

00:03:38.199 --> 00:03:45.559
easy for you to sort of search through the variable namespace in an automated fashion.

00:03:45.559 --> 00:03:50.639
Filter is analogous to select, except instead of selecting columns, it brings back rows,

00:03:50.639 --> 00:03:56.440
or if your data's tidy, these would be observations. And the way filter works is you give it a

00:03:56.440 --> 00:04:02.520
logical test. So here I'm giving it the test where wind is greater than or equal to 50.

00:04:02.520 --> 00:04:05.960
What filter will do is it will apply that test to each row in your data frame and give

00:04:05.960 --> 00:04:14.240
you back just the rows that pass the test. You can combine tests by putting a comma in

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:17.519
between tests, and what filter will do is it will combine them as if there was an and

00:04:17.519 --> 00:04:22.000
statement between them. So these are only the rows where the wind is greater than 50

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:27.519
and the name, the storm name, is in Alberto, Alex, and Allison. If you want to do an or

00:04:27.519 --> 00:04:32.559
condition, we'll just use the Boolean operator for or and r to combine two tests into a single

00:04:32.559 --> 00:04:39.079
test. That's the pipe operator. So filter works best if you know how to use logical

00:04:39.079 --> 00:04:44.559
tests in R, and here's a quick list of the logical tests that exist in R. The table on

00:04:44.559 --> 00:04:49.440
the right are Boolean operators. These combine two or more logical tests into a single logical

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:54.079
test, so you'll get a single true or false, and the ones on the left actually do logical

00:04:54.079 --> 00:05:00.880
operations. You'll notice at the bottom that is.na and !is.na are in there, which means

00:05:00.880 --> 00:05:06.279
filter is a great way to winnow out rows that have na values if you combine it with is.na

00:05:06.279 --> 00:05:15.559
or !is.na. All right. The mutate function takes your data frame and it returns a copy

00:05:15.559 --> 00:05:19.839
of the data frame with new variables added to it. Normally these will be variables that

