you derive from the variables that exist in your data. So before we had sort of the

00:05:24.359 --> 00:05:30.519
bogus example of calculating a ratio variable from the wind and pressure variable in storms,

00:05:30.519 --> 00:05:34.119
the information in that ratio variable was in the data to begin with, it just wasn't

00:05:34.119 --> 00:05:39.359
on display, but you could logically derive it from the data that's there, and this is

00:05:39.359 --> 00:05:46.600
how you do it with mutate. You run mutate on the data frame you want to add to or change,

00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:50.880
then you give it the name of the new column you want to make, and you set that equal to

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:55.559
some expression that will make the values of the new column. You can make more than

00:05:55.559 --> 00:06:00.320
one column at the same time, and you can even use a column to make a new column in the same

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:06.119
command. Make sure that the first column appears before the columns that rely on it. So here

00:06:06.119 --> 00:06:11.260
inverse relies on ratio, and since ratio appears first, inverse will be able to find ratio

00:06:11.260 --> 00:06:18.739
and use it to calculate inverse. This command, mutate, doesn't actually affect your original

00:06:18.739 --> 00:06:23.220
data frame, it returns a data frame that has the new variables added to it. So if you want

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:29.299
to save that data frame and use those variables later, you'll need to assign it to an object.

00:06:29.299 --> 00:06:33.200
There are a lot of functions that are useful to use with mutate to make new variables.

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:37.700
This is a short list of them. This list, by the way, also appears on that cheat sheet

00:06:37.700 --> 00:06:44.059
you can download from the RStudio website. And each of these functions has something

00:06:44.059 --> 00:06:49.739
in common. They all take a vector and return a vector of the same length. So if you want

00:06:49.739 --> 00:06:53.299
to add a column onto your data frame, that column's going to have to have values for

00:06:53.299 --> 00:06:58.179
each row in the data frame. When you use these functions, you'll get a set of values that

00:06:58.179 --> 00:07:02.459
will fit right up with your data frame. You can call these window functions, because they

00:07:02.619 --> 00:07:08.779
pass the whole vector through a window and the vector changes, but each element is still

00:07:08.779 --> 00:07:17.700
represented at the end. So the last of those four functions we listed was summarize. Summarize

00:07:17.700 --> 00:07:21.820
takes a data frame and it calculates summary statistics from it. You get back a new data

00:07:21.820 --> 00:07:26.339
frame, and usually that new data frame is much, much smaller. For example, here I'm

00:07:26.339 --> 00:07:30.859
summarizing the pollution data frame by calculating the median value of the amount. I only need

00:07:30.859 --> 00:07:36.420
one value to show the median, so my new data frame only has one row. I'm also calculating

00:07:36.420 --> 00:07:42.579
the variance. Summarize works similar to mutate. You give it the name of the new columns you

00:07:42.579 --> 00:07:48.059
want in your new summary data frame, and then you set those names equal to the R code that

00:07:48.059 --> 00:08:00.220
will build those values. Like mutate, there's functions that seem to work best with summarize,

00:08:00.739 --> 00:08:08.339
things like the standard statistical estimators, min, mean, variance, standard deviation, median.

00:08:08.339 --> 00:08:14.179
All these functions are similar to each other in a part way. Unlike the window functions

00:08:14.179 --> 00:08:17.980
used with mutate, these functions actually all take a vector or a group of numbers and

00:08:17.980 --> 00:08:22.179
return a single number. So you could think of them as summarizing functions or summary

00:08:22.179 --> 00:08:28.100
functions. When you use summarize, you'll want to use these summarizing functions to

00:08:28.100 --> 00:08:37.859
build your summary statistics. There's one more function in dplyr that doesn't really

00:08:37.859 --> 00:08:43.380
add to your data or subtract from it, but you can consider it like a fifth horseman

00:08:43.380 --> 00:08:47.500
of dplyr, and that's a range. What a range will do is it will rearrange the order of

00:08:47.500 --> 00:08:52.500
the rows in your data frame based on the value of one of the columns. So here I rearranged

00:08:52.500 --> 00:08:57.219
the rows in storms based on the value of wind. And if we color-coded this data set, you could

00:08:57.219 --> 00:09:04.099
see that, it's easier to see, that whereas before the rows were not ordered by wind value,

00:09:04.099 --> 00:09:07.619
now they go from the row with the smallest wind value to the row with the highest wind

00:09:07.619 --> 00:09:14.179
value. If you want to reorder them in a different way, in descending order, you can use this

00:09:14.179 --> 00:09:19.020
helper function DESC, it stands for descend, and just wrap that around the variable whose

00:09:19.020 --> 00:09:24.419
